    <title>Combined summary - Merkleize All The Things</title>
    <updated>2023-06-16T03:08:29.053459+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2022-November/021182.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>Salvatore Ingala has proposed a method for enabling general smart contracts in Bitcoin using covenants. This involves adding restrictions on the outputs of transactions spending UTXOs, called covenants, which has various benefits including minimal impact on layer 1, generality, compatibility with P2TR, and no new cryptographic assumptions required. The proposal uses Merkle trees and a challenge protocol for UTXO-based smart contracts, providing fully recursive constructions with an arbitrary depth of covenant execution. The article explores potential use cases of the covenant technique, including state channels, CoinPool, ZK-proofs in L2 protocols, and optimistic rollups. Email conversations discuss various topics related to smart contracts and fraud-proof systems in Bitcoin. Discussions cover the use of Merkle trees, covenants, and challenge protocols to enable general smart contracts in the UTXO model. One proposed construction involves a universal state channel where parties can enter any contract among themselves entirely inside the channel. Additionally, the email proposes building a universal state channel where people can use any contract they want without publishing it on the blockchain. Various examples are given, including rock-paper-scissors game and tic-tac-toe, to demonstrate the implementation of MATT smart contracts using CICV/COCV and CTV hashes. The discussions also cover game theory and how with the right economic incentives, protocol designers can guarantee that playing a losing game always loses money compared to cooperating. Salvatore proposed using rock-paper-scissors as an academic example for the MATT (Miniscript + adaptor signatures + taproot) smart contract. In an email exchange, Johan Torås Halseth and Salvatore Ingala discuss the generalization of a construct that allows access to embedded data in inputs and outputs, as well as enforcement of output keys and taptrees.The context also discusses various proposals related to smart contracts and scalability. One proposal involved the use of universal Turing machine as a function f in a contract, allowing for fraud proofs to be done on statements "f(code, data) == output" and enabling parties to enter any contract among themselves entirely inside the channel. The bisection protocol was discussed, which is used in a larger protocol that ensures scalability by not ending up on the chain and only resulting in a longer chain of transactions in case of a challenge. Discussions also covered the use of verkle trees instead of merkle trees for lower size and cost, but implementation complexity and new cryptographic assumptions were pointed out.Overall, the context discusses various proposals and constructions related to smart contracts in Bitcoin, including the use of covenants, Merkle trees, and challenge protocols. The potential benefits and use cases of these proposals are explored, with various examples given to demonstrate their implementation. Discussions also cover game theory and strategies for ensuring cooperation among participants in smart contract systems.</summary>
